+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>
+    <string name="passionate">Passionate Android Developer. Connect with me.</string>
+    <string name="info_know">Info you must Know about Android !</string>
+    <string name="whatisroot">What is Root ?</string>
+    <string name="whyroot">Why Root ?</string>
+    <string name="rootinfo">Root Info</string>
+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamless">What are Seamless System Updates?</string>
+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whyroot">Why Root ?</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisroot">What is Root ?</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. +    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisseamless">सीमलेस सिस्टम अपडेट क्या हैं?</string>
+    <string name="whatisrootstat">कई कंप्यूटर ऑपरेटिंग सिस्टम के लिए रूट (प्रशासक या सुपरयूज़र) खाता एक विशेष उपयोगकर्ता है जो सभी फ़ाइलों और आदेशों तक पूरी पहुंच रखता है। एंड्रॉइड के संदर्भ में, रूट एक्सेस उपयोगकर्ता को डिवाइस पर पूर्ण नियंत्रण रखने की अनुमति देता है। रूट एक्सेस वाले उपयोगकर्ता नुकसान का कारण बन सकते हैं और सावधानी बरती जानी चाहिए।</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">रूट एक्सेस प्राप्त करने के सबसे सामान्य कारण हैं: \n• अनवांटेड एप्लिकेशन निकालें \n• प्रदर्शन बढ़ाएँ \n• पूर्ण डेटा बैकअप निष्पादित करें \n• कनेक्ट करें WiFi और यूएसबी Tether \n• कस्टम थीम्स का उपयोग करें \n• और, नवीनतम चलाएं एंड्राइड ओएस। \nमूल पहुँच से प्राप्त लाभ डिवाइस के हार्डवेयर और सॉफ़्टवेयर के आधार पर भिन्न होते हैं।</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">प्रोजेक्ट ट्रेबल एक नए विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस के माध्यम से एंड्रॉइड ओएस फ्रेमवर्क से विक्रेता कार्यान्वयन (सिलिकॉन द्वारा लिखित डिवाइस-विशिष्ट, निचले स्तर के सॉफ़्टवेयर) को अलग करता है। एंड्रॉइड 7.x और पहले के संस्करण में, कोई औपचारिक विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस मौजूद नहीं है, इसलिए डिवाइस निर्माताओं को डिवाइस को एंड्रॉइड के नए संस्करण में स्थानांतरित करने के लिए एंड्रॉइड कोड के बड़े हिस्से को अपडेट करना होगा।</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">ट्रेबल के साथ, एक नया स्थिर विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस एंड्रॉइड के हार्डवेयर-विशिष्ट भागों तक पहुंच प्रदान करता है, जो डिवाइस निर्माताओं को केवल एंड्रॉइड ओएस फ्रेमवर्क को अपडेट करके नए एंड्रॉइड रिलीज़ प्रदान करने में सक्षम बनाता है - बिना सिलिकॉन निर्माताओं से आवश्यक अतिरिक्त काम के।</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A / B सिस्टम अपडेट, जिसे सहज अपडेट के रूप में भी जाना जाता है, सुनिश्चित करें कि ओवर-द-एयर (OTA) अपडेट के दौरान डिस्क पर एक कार्यशील बूटिंग सिस्टम रहता है। यह दृष्टिकोण एक अद्यतन के बाद एक निष्क्रिय डिवाइस की संभावना को कम करता है, जिसका अर्थ है कि कम डिवाइस रिप्लेसमेंट और मरम्मत और वारंटी केंद्रों पर डिवाइस रीफ्लेश। अन्य वाणिज्यिक-ग्रेड ऑपरेटिंग सिस्टम जैसे क्रोमओएस भी ए / बी अपडेट का सफलतापूर्वक उपयोग करते हैं।</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">कई कंप्यूटर ऑपरेटिंग सिस्टम के लिए रूट (प्रशासक या सुपरयूज़र) खाता एक विशेष उपयोगकर्ता है जो सभी फ़ाइलों और आदेशों तक पूरी पहुंच रखता है। एंड्रॉइड के संदर्भ में, रूट एक्सेस उपयोगकर्ता को डिवाइस पर पूर्ण नियंत्रण रखने की अनुमति देता है। रूट एक्सेस वाले उपयोगकर्ता नुकसान का कारण बन सकते हैं और सावधानी बरती जानी चाहिए।</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">रूट एक्सेस प्राप्त करने के सबसे सामान्य कारण हैं: \n• अनवांटेड एप्लिकेशन निकालें \n• प्रदर्शन बढ़ाएँ \n• पूर्ण डेटा बैकअप निष्पादित करें \n• कनेक्ट करें WiFi और यूएसबी Tether \n• कस्टम थीम्स का उपयोग करें \n• और, नवीनतम चलाएं एंड्राइड ओएस। \nमूल पहुँच से प्राप्त लाभ डिवाइस के हार्डवेयर और सॉफ़्टवेयर के आधार पर भिन्न होते हैं।</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">प्रोजेक्ट ट्रेबल एक नए विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस के माध्यम से एंड्रॉइड ओएस फ्रेमवर्क से विक्रेता कार्यान्वयन (सिलिकॉन द्वारा लिखित डिवाइस-विशिष्ट, निचले स्तर के सॉफ़्टवेयर) को अलग करता है। एंड्रॉइड 7.x और पहले के संस्करण में, कोई औपचारिक विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस मौजूद नहीं है, इसलिए डिवाइस निर्माताओं को डिवाइस को एंड्रॉइड के नए संस्करण में स्थानांतरित करने के लिए एंड्रॉइड कोड के बड़े हिस्से को अपडेट करना होगा।</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">ट्रेबल के साथ, एक नया स्थिर विक्रेता इंटरफ़ेस एंड्रॉइड के हार्डवेयर-विशिष्ट भागों तक पहुंच प्रदान करता है, जो डिवाइस निर्माताओं को केवल एंड्रॉइड ओएस फ्रेमवर्क को अपडेट करके नए एंड्रॉइड रिलीज़ प्रदान करने में सक्षम बनाता है - बिना सिलिकॉन निर्माताओं से आवश्यक अतिरिक्त काम के।</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A / B सिस्टम अपडेट, जिसे सहज अपडेट के रूप में भी जाना जाता है, सुनिश्चित करें कि ओवर-द-एयर (OTA) अपडेट के दौरान डिस्क पर एक कार्यशील बूटिंग सिस्टम रहता है। यह दृष्टिकोण एक अद्यतन के बाद एक निष्क्रिय डिवाइस की संभावना को कम करता है, जिसका अर्थ है कि कम डिवाइस रिप्लेसमेंट और मरम्मत और वारंटी केंद्रों पर डिवाइस रीफ्लेश। अन्य वाणिज्यिक-ग्रेड ऑपरेटिंग सिस्टम जैसे क्रोमओएस भी ए / बी अपडेट का सफलतापूर्वक उपयोग करते हैं।</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. +    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="info_know">Info you must Know about Android !</string>
+    <string name="whatisroot">What is Root ?</string>
+    <string name="whyroot">Why Root ?</string>
+    <string name="rootinfo">Root Info</string>
+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamless">What are Seamless System Updates?</string>
+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisroot">What is Root ?</string>
+    <string name="whyroot">Why Root ?</string>

+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamless">What are Seamless System Updates?</string>
+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisroot">What is Root ?</string>
+    <string name="whyroot">Why Root ?</string>

+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamless">What are Seamless System Updates?</string>
+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatistreble">What is Project Treble ?</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

+    <string name="app_desc">Device Info is a simple and powerful Android application which gives you a complete Software and Hardware information about your Mobile device with advanced user-interface.\nIf possible help me in translating the app in your local language. +    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>

Tap on translate and you will be redirected to Crowdin website. Login there and start contributing.</string>

+    <string name="whatisrootstat">For many computer operating systems the root (Administrator or Superuser) account is a special user with complete access to all files and commands. In the context of Android,root access allows the user to have complete control over the device. Users with root access can cause damage and caution should be used.</string>
+    <string name="whyrootstat">The most common reasons for gaining root access are:\n• Remove Unwanted Applications\n• Increase Performance\n• Perform Full Data Backup\n• Connect WiFi and USB Tether\n• Use Custom Themes\n• And, run the latest Android OS.\nAll the benefits gained from root access vary based on the Hardware and Software of the device.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat1">Project Treble separates the vendor implementation(device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new vendor interface. In Android 7.x and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of Android.</string>
+    <string name="whatistreblestat2">With Treble, a new stable vendor interface provides access to the hardware-specific parts of Android, enabling device makers to deliver new Android releases simply by updating the Android OS framework - without any additional work required from the silicon manufacturers.</string>
+    <string name="whatisseamlessstat">A/B system updates, also known as seamless updates, ensure a workable booting system remains on the disk during an over-the-air (OTA) update. This approach reduces the likelihood of an inactive device after an update, which means fewer device replacements and device reflashes at repair and warranty centers. Other commercial-grade operating systems such as ChromeOS also use A/B updates successfully.</string>
